[1]
Date: Tue, 25 Oct 2005
From: Pablo Nart <pablo12@hotPOP.com>
Source: Brownfield Network [edited]
<http://www.brownfieldnetwork.com/gestalt/go.cfm?objectid=287636BE-CA50-79E3-DA52AB6E49E2AE67>

Brazil's Agriculture Ministry has confirmed several new cases of foot and
mouth disease (FMD) on 6 ranches in Mato Grasso do Sul, near the border
with Parana; that brings the total number of farms infected in that state
to 10. There are 4 reported cases in Parana that have not been confirmed by
Sao Paulo.
The Ag Ministry expects more than 10 000 animals to be culled in Mato
Grasso do Sul, the source of nearly half of all cattle exported from the
world's top beef-selling nation.
Since the initial outbreak 2 weeks ago, 41 nations have banned meat imports
from Brazil. Depending on how long the bans last, this FMD outbreak could
cost Brazil upwards of $1 billion.
--
